Jeremy
3.0 out of 5 stars\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n \n \n Should have gotten a 4090 -_-\n \n
Reviewed in the United States on 7 April 2023
Verified Purchase
\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n \n \n Knocks the socks right off my 2080 Super, as it should -- but let's be honest, at $1200, the 4080 is ridiculously overpriced. This card should be in the $700 range!

Check clearances. You'd be hard pressed to fit this in most standard ATX chassis unless you are mounting vertically, which CAN be bad for temps if you lack common sense. For a server chassis, don't bother with anything under 5u. Speaking of, you can't get 5u really outside of industrial channels, except Silverstone, and that chassis is also absurdly overpriced. Sliger has nothing ATM.

Probably gonna want to go ahead and order a direct to PSU right angled 12VHPWR cable. Why? Because if mounting horizontally, good luck closing your case panel. If mounting vertically, it's just plain ugly.
Also - go with a boutique place like Ensourced OR go with a trusted manufacturer like Corsair, CableMod, etc. as opposed to taking a chance on one of the no name nickel knights that are peddling cheapo 12VHPWR cables and adapters. Unless you are cold and want a fire. Then maybe not a bad idea.

The TUF itself is probably the most ridiculously sized card I have ever seen. Absolute Unit. The Robocop of Video Cards. I personally loathe RGB and gamer aesthetic, and minus the silly plastic TUF logo, it doesn't look awful. If Nvidia's own FE cards are the aesthetic adults in the room, the TUF cards are the Division 1 Defensive Linemen progeny.

All in all, its fine. Super overpriced. Runs games well, but is way too large.

And some quick non pro benchmarks, 3440x1440, 32GB DDR4CL16, 5950X, NVME, everything Ultra, DLSS/Frame Generation enabled if present.
Game - FPS
Control - ~60
TLOU - 60-70
CP2077 - 100
SOF2 - 300+\n \n
